      "comment_id" : 40432604,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "Right click on your workspace directory and make sure it is not &quot;Read Only&quot; in case of windows and has &quot;Read and Write&quot; permission for user in case of *nix. I think if you have used a workspace created by some other user and directly pointed it to your Eclipse then this issue may occur."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3349438,
      "reputation" : 519,
      "user_id" : 2813770,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 41,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/080d12ac430e8d90be4f73c9670f173e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Parth Bhagat",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2813770/parth-bhagat"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1410673037,
    "creation_date" : 1410673037,
    "answer_id" : 25830419,
    "question_id" : 25830342,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Check whether the workspace on which works has write permission in your file system or not.</p>\n\n<p>In case of jar archive make sure you have added that jar file in your class path using 'java buildpath'. If you have added that reference to your project then it will definitely work.</p>\n\n<p>If an already referenced project works then according to me you have problem of access rights. You may not have permission to write/append your .classpath file.</p>\n\n<p>Hope you have performed below steps to add project reference.</p>\n\n<p>Right click project -> Build path -> Configure buildpath... -> Project tab -> Add... -> Then add project from current workspace</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4364861,
      "reputation" : 587,
      "user_id" : 3560966,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/o5gKO.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Paul Cuddihy",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3560966/paul-cuddihy"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1657286421,
    "creation_date" : 1657286421,
    "answer_id" : 72912053,
    "question_id" : 25830342,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Years later, on Eclipse Version: 2022-03 (4.23.0) I've also had issues linking source code of dependent maven module projects. I found <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/users/2813770/parth-bhagat\">parth's</a> answer got me started but there's a few more details.</p>\n<p>Right click the parent project and select <strong>Build path -&gt; Configure buildpath</strong>...</p>\n<ul>\n<li>on <strong>&quot;Project&quot; tab</strong> - use the <strong>Add</strong> button to add the eclipse project</li>\n<li>on <strong>&quot;Order and Export&quot; tab</strong> - use the <strong>Up</strong> button to move the eclipse project higher than the JRE System Library and Maven Dependencies</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Upon returning to the code in the parent project and hitting <strong>F3</strong> on a class name from the child project, eclipse will now bring me to the child project source code.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5911929,
      "reputation" : 107,
      "user_id" : 4651877,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-FohLfwXC6vE/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAJFM/p7EmFcJZrmM/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "Marko Adam",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4651877/marko-adam"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1759475870,
    "creation_date" : 1759475870,
    "answer_id" : 79781520,
    "question_id" : 25830342,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>What worked for me is deleting the <code>.metadata/.plugins/org.eclipse.jdt.core</code> folder inside workspace. And then restarting Eclipse.</p>\n<p>That forces reindexing of project.</p>\n"
  } ],
